    "plan_content": "Here's the full implementation plan I've designed after studying the codebase:\n\n---\n\n## Plan: Stepper Compound Component\n\n### Architecture Decision\nFollows **`carousel.tsx`'s pure-React context pattern** (no Radix UI — no relevant primitive exists). Two contexts are needed:\n- `StepperContext` — root-level, shared by all children: `activeStep` + `orientation`\n- `StepperItemContext` — per-item: `step` + derived `state` (`\"completed\" | \"active\" | \"pending\"`)\n\nEach context gets a `useStepper()` / `useStepperItem()` hook that throws a helpful error if used outside the provider.\n\n### 4 Changes Total\n\n**CREATE: `ui/stepper.tsx`** — 7 named exports:\n| Export | Notes |\n|---|---|\n| `Stepper` | Wraps `StepperContext.Provider`, `data-slot=\"stepper\"`, `data-orientation` |\n| `StepperItem` | Derives `state` from `activeStep`, wraps `StepperItemContext.Provider`, `data-state` + `data-step` |\n| `StepperTrigger` | `<button>` with colored circle — filled/outlined/muted based on state; falls back to step number if no children |\n| `StepperTitle` | `<p>` with `text-sm font-medium` |\n| `StepperDescription` | `<p>` with `text-sm text-muted-foreground` |\n| `StepperSeparator` | Reads both contexts; fills `bg-primary` when item is \"completed\" (= when user advances past it) |\n| `StepperContent` | Returns `null` when `step !== activeStep` |\n\n**CREATE: `examples/stepper-demo.tsx`** — 3-step interactive demo (\"Account\" → \"Profile\" → \"Complete\") with `React.useState(1)` for `activeStep`, clickable triggers, content panels per step, and Previous/Next navigation.\n\n**MODIFY: `ui/_registry.ts`** — append `{ name: \"stepper\", type: \"registry:ui\", files: [...] }` before line 705's `]`\n\n**MODIFY: `examples/_registry.ts`** — append `{ name: \"stepper-demo\", type: \"registry:example\", registryDependencies: [\"stepper\"], files: [...] }` before line 2651's `]`\n\n### Key design note on `StepperSeparator`\nThe separator is placed **inside** `StepperItem` (not between items as siblings). It reads the parent item's `state` — filling when `\"completed\"`. This naturally satisfies \"visual state changes when the NEXT step is completed\": when the user advances, the current item becomes `\"completed\"` and its separator fills, visually indicating the path to the next step is complete.",
